1 Abstract

This study aims to replicate the findings of Price & Viceisza (2023), which examine the role of Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUâs) in improving educational and economic outcomes for Black students. The replication process was conducted using R, leveraging publicly available data sets such as the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES), Gallup, and the MSI Data Project. By systematically collecting, processing, and analyzing these data sets, the study reconstructs three key tables that compare student outcomes between HBCUâs and non-HBCUâs. The methodology involves data pre-processing, statistical computations, and visualization, ensuring transparency and reproducibility. The results validate the original studyâs conclusions, reinforcing the positive impact of HBCUâs on graduation rates, economic mobility, and student satisfaction. This replication highlights the significance of open-access data and computational reproducibility in social science research while paving the way for further studies exploring institutional effectiveness and policy impacts.

2 Introduction

Replicating a study in R usually involves a workflow of loading, cleaning and analyzing data sets in an attempt confirm the findings of a study. For instance, in Price & Viceisza (2023), their replication package is exclusively geared towards generating three foundation tables using publicly available data sources such as the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES), Gallup and the MSI Data Project.

We start with the function importing the data into R (read. csv() or read_excel(), and then manipulated the data with dplyr or tidyverse packages, filtering and transforming variables of interest. Calculating summary statistics and making comparison between HBCUs and other colleges is done with functions.such as summary(), group_by(), and mutate().

These workflows are scripted and show each step taken in the analysis pipeline to ensure it can be reproduced. For export of results into formatted tables xtable() (LaTeX) or kable() (Markdown) are used. The data and code are publicly available in the replication package for transparency.

3 Objective

The primary aim behind replication in R is to reproduce and validate the findings presented by Price & Viceisza (2023) concerning the effects of Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs) on the higher education achievements of black scholars. Conveniently, based on this replication using other existing, publicly available data sets by prior research studies (NCES, Gallup and the MSI Data Project), we are able to ensure the accuracy and validity of this studyâs findings. This is dangerously useful to the research in both economic and social sciences as it will increase transparency, credibility and reproducibility, hence allows other researchers to add to the body of knowledge delivering outcomes which other can validate.

This is mainly aimed at creating systematic processing and analyzing the data sets that yield statistical values similar to those in the release study. Such process requires data cleansing, transformation and statistical computations with R programming language to emulate the three major tables delivered in the study. Finally, by scripting the steps taken for the analysis in R, the second goal of the replication is to showcase best practices of empirical research, which help in providing both reliable and reproducible data manipulation and statistical tests.

Moreover, the replication process helps advocate for institutions like HBCUs that improve student success across metrics like graduation rates and economic mobility. The replication validates the robustness of the studyâs findings, which helps ensure that policy discussions and educational reforms based on their results are founded on reliable empirical evidence. The method also provides a roadmap to other researchers who might be interested in attempting similar replication work, emphasizing the importance of data integrity and replicability in social science research.

4 Methodology

To validate the results of Price & Viceisza (2023), we follow a strict methodology and use R to replicate the process. This approach starts with the collection of the data, which are publicly available data sets from the NCES, the Gallup, and the MSI Data Project that are accessed and downloaded. These data sets include important variables pertaining to the enrollment, graduation and post-graduate outcomes of students at HBCUâs and non-HBCUâs.

Then comes the data cleaning and pre-processing step, where observations we are interested in are filtered, handling missing data, and processing variables to be in line with the origin study. R packages including dplyr and tidyverse are used for this step, as they allow for manipulating and structuring data. They are followed by functions such as summary(), group_by(), and mutate() to generate key descriptive statistics and comparisons. This is followed by data preparation, statistical analyses and replication of tables. Finally, replication output is validated against the results of the original study to check for consistency.

5 R

What does R language mean? R is a free software programming language used for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing. Thanks to its versatility, extensive package ecosystem, and solid visualization capabilities, it is commonly utilized in academia, research, and industry. Created by Ross Ihaka and Robert Gentleman in the early 1990s, R has established itself as a go-to tool for data scientists, economists, and statisticians.

So, why R? Do you know that R has a complete package system? And, thanks to popular R packages (e.g., the tidyverse (dplyr, ggplot2, tidyr) isolates, efficient data manipulation and visualization; lm(), glm() fit additional statistical models. Statistical methods like regression, autism, t-tests, etc., can be moted easily in R, Therefore R is also useful in seamless machine learning, time series analysis, econometrics through specialized libraries like caret, forecast, plm, etc.

Therefore, R is a very popular tool in replication studies, data science, and research in general, thanks to its ability to produce reproducible pipelines and dynamic reporting via R Markdown and Shiny applications. It seamlessly works with other tools such as Python, SQL and Tableau to make it a versatile solution for modern-day data analytics. R is now one of the most important language used for statistical analysis and reproducible research with a large user community in an active development of new methods.

6 R Markdown

R Markdown â An integrated, inter-active document system that can mix code (R), results (tables, plot, numbersâ¦) and text (Markdown syntax) in one document. It supports a number of output formats (HTML, PDF, Word) and perhaps is primarily used for reproducible research, reports, and presentations. Users can create documents that stimuli narrative with R code chunks that they fill in R Markdown. This is commonly used in research and academic fields to ensure transparency and replicability in data-driven studies.

R Quarto â the successor to R Markdown â comes with better flexibility and formatting, as well as improved table rendering capabilities. However, unlike R Markdown, Quarto likes whatever language you wish, maybe Python, Julia, Observable JS, besides R, not excluding better table rendering. If your project requires robust support for tables (e.g.Â replication studies, economic research), Quarto has better table formatting capabilities than R Markdown.

7.1 Data Collection for Each Table

The replication process in R relies on publicly available datasets to generate the key tables from Price and Viceisza (2023). The data sources for each table are as follows:

7.1.1 Table 1: Characteristics of Selected HBCUs

  • Data Source: MSI Data Project (available at : https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/jep.37.3.213)

The data were filtered for institutions classified as âHistorically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUâs)â using the i_hbcuipeds variable. The data set was further refined by selecting only four-year institutions and sorting them based on enrollment size to include the largest HBCUs.

By following the replication process instructions provided in Readme file, table 1 is replicated as shown in SectionÂ 8 .

7.1.2 Table 2: Educational and Labor Market Outcomes

  • Data Source: MSI Data Project (available at : https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/b&b/index.asp)

Specific survey years (1993/2003 and 2008/2018 cohorts) were selected to analyze long-term educational and labor market outcomes. Filters were applied to focus on Black students, distinguishing between those who attended HBCUâs and non-HBCUâs.

By following the replication process instructions provided in Readme file, table 1 is replicated as shown in SectionÂ 9 .

7.1.3 Table 3: Student Support and Experiential Learning Opportunities

  • Data Source: âGallup-USA Funds Minority College Graduates Reportâ (available at : https://www.gallup.com/services/186359/gallup-usa-funds-minority-college-graduates-report-pdf.aspx).

The survey was conducted among Black college graduates, comparing those from **HBCUâs vs.Â non-HBCUâsâ on key support metrics. Variables such as faculty mentorship, applied learning experiences, and extracurricular involvement were included in the analysis.

By following the replication process instructions provided in Readme file, table 1 is replicated as shown in SectionÂ 10 .

rm(list = ls()) # clear Environment

# Define required packages
required_packages <- c("tidyverse", "haven", "dplyr", "readxl", "writexl","knitr")

# Install and load required packages
install_if_missing <- function(pkg) {
  if (!require(pkg, character.only = TRUE)) {
    install.packages(pkg, dependencies = TRUE)
    library(pkg, character.only = TRUE)
  }
}
# Apply function to each package
lapply(required_packages, install_if_missing)

8.3 Code for replication of table 1

The Readme file clearly provides the necessary step to replicate table 1. By following the steps the table 1 can be generated. By using kable() we can generate the table in quadro html file.

CODE:

# Filter for HBCU's (Column DN = 'i_hbcuipeds')
HBCU_i_hbcuipeds_filtered <- table_1_data |> 
  filter(i_hbcuipeds == "Yes")
view(HBCU_i_hbcuipeds_filtered)

# Filter to keep only Year 2021 (Column I = 'year')
HBCU_year_filtered <- HBCU_i_hbcuipeds_filtered |> 
  filter(year == 2021)
view(HBCU_year_filtered)
  
# Selecting the colomns required for replication process
HBCU_i_fte12mn_filtered <- HBCU_year_filtered |> 
  select(instname, control, year, i_fte12mn, m_state, m_pell_pct,grate_black)
view(HBCU_i_fte12mn_filtered) 

# Select the 11 largest institutions based on enrollment (Column FL = 'i_fte12mn')
HBCU_des_filtered <- HBCU_i_fte12mn_filtered |> 
  mutate(i_fte12mn = as.numeric(i_fte12mn))|> 
  arrange(desc(i_fte12mn))|> 
  slice_head(n = 11)
view(HBCU_des_filtered) 

# Exclude St. Philipâs College (which has i_fte12mn == 6429)
HBCU_exclude_filtered <- HBCU_des_filtered |> 
  filter(i_fte12mn != 6429)
view(HBCU_exclude_filtered)   

# Include additional specific institutions based on enrollment values
HBCU_add_filtered <- table_1_data |> 
  filter(i_hbcuipeds == "Yes") |> 
  filter(year == 2021) |>
  select(instname, control, year, i_fte12mn, m_state, m_pell_pct,grate_black) |> 
  filter(i_fte12mn %in% c(4510, 3276, 3133, 2296, 2261, 2173)) |> 
  mutate(i_fte12mn = as.numeric(i_fte12mn))
view(HBCU_add_filtered)

# Combine both data sets 
combo_HBCU_table <- bind_rows(HBCU_exclude_filtered, HBCU_add_filtered)
view(combo_HBCU_table)

# Convert grate_black into percentage from numeric
final_HBCU_table <- combo_HBCU_table  |> 
  mutate(grate_black = as.numeric(grate_black)) |> 
  mutate(grate_black = paste0(grate_black * 100,"%"))
view(final_HBCU_table)
  
# Rename columns to generate the table 1
HBCU_table_1 <- final_HBCU_table |>
  rename(
    Institution = instname,
    State = m_state,
    Type = control,
    Enrollment = i_fte12mn,
    `Pell Percent` = m_pell_pct,
    `6-Year Black Graduation Rate` = grate_black
  )
view(HBCU_table_1)

11 Challenges faced during replication

11.1 Challenges in replicating table 1

  • In Readme file âi_hbcipedsâ is given as column DM but it is under column DN.
  • In Readme file âi_fete12mnâ is given as column FK but it is under Column FL.
  • Columns m_city,i_landgrnt,i_c18basic is not required for the replication process of table 1 as per Readme file.
  • âi_fete12mnâ has character values that need to be converted to numeric values.
  • The output of the table 1 in pdf is displayed beyond the margins. A proper solution could not be found to solve this issue. It is however visible in the standalone. html fime uploaded in the repository.

11.2 Challenges in replicating table 2

  • Incomplete instructions when it comes to filter application in website that is required to attain the required data set values in Readme file (percentage information missing). Was later observed in the data set provided in the replication package, which assisted in acquiring proper data set values.
  • No instructions provided for the replication process of table 2. Readme file only provides information on acquiring the required data set.
  • Data setâs complexity made data-processing time consuming.
  • Unable to remove Na values in output table. which can be seen in replicated output of table 2 in SectionÂ 9.1

11.3 Challenges in replicating table 3

  • No data set available in csv/ xlsx format but the replication package contains table 3 in â.xlsxâ format.
  • Cannot reference Gallup report as itâs bibtex file was not found.
  • The output of the table 3 in pdf is displayed beyond the margins. A proper solution could not be found to solve this issue. It is however visible in the standalone. html fime uploaded in the repository.

13.1 Future scope

Future Scope

Replicating the findings of Price & Viceisza (2023) using R opens several avenues for future research opportunities and methodological advances. A significant opportunity for growth is the inclusion of more data sets, such as longitudinal labor market surveys or administrative education data, to strengthen our comparative studies between HBCUâs and non-HBCUâs.

Future studies may also use machine learning techniques to identify predictive features of graduation rates and economic mobility outcomes among Black students.
